problem:
A heavy disk of radius $R$ is rolling downwards, unwinding two strings in the process. The strings are attached to
the ceiling and always remain under tension during the motion.
What was the magnitude of velocity of the disk’s centre when
its angular velocity was $\omega$ and the angle between the strings
was $\alpha$?
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=5.5cm]{kalda_k44.png}
    \end{center}

solution:
First we use idea 1.2 -- that the velocity of the string unrolling is $\omega R$. Thus, the velocity of the cylinder projected onto the two strings must be $\omega R$. Thus, we can draw the following diagram:
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=4cm]{rolllyyy].png}
    \end{center}
    Thus, we can see that $v = \frac{\omega R}{\cos \alpha / 2}$.

